    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-08-07T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-08-07T02:00:00-05:00" n="740"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d740">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Secretary’s Memoranda of Conversation, lot 64 D
                    199</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Assistant Secretary of
                        State for Far Eastern Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_RWS1"
                            >Robertson</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Seoul</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1953-08-07T16:00:00+09:00">August 7, 1953—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>Fourth Meeting Between President <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                            >Rhee</persName> and Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                            >Dulles</persName>. President <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                        >Rhee</persName>’s Residence.</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>Participants:</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_ROK1">
                            <hi rend="italic">ROK</hi>
                        </gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>President <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_PTC1">Paik</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Defense Minister <persName corresp="#p_SWIA1">Sohn</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_LBC1">Limb</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Dr. <persName corresp="#p_ORT1">Oliver</persName> (Adviser to President
                            <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>)</item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName>Kim</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">United States</hi>
                    </item>
                    <item>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_TLGMD1">General Maxwell Taylor</persName>, Commanding
                        General, Eighth Army</item>
                    <item>Assistant Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RWS1">Walter S.
                            Robertson</persName>, Bureau of Far Eastern Affairs</item>
                </list>
                <p>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> presented a draft
                    proposed joint statement to be made by President <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                        >Rhee</persName> and Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>
                    upon conclusion of the consultations. Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                        >Dulles</persName> suggested that the Americans retire while the draft was
                    under consideration by the Koreans. After approximately thirty minutes, we were
                    called back into the conference. Certain <pb facs="0371" n="1489"
                        xml:id="pg_1489"/> minor changes in the text suggested by Foreign Minister
                        <persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName> were accepted by the Secretary
                    without discussion.</p>
                <p>Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName> then proposed the
                    addition of a paragraph to the effect that it was agreed that the <gloss
                        target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> has complete sovereignty over its domestic
                    affairs, <hi rend="italic">including</hi> the right to drive the Chinese
                    Communist invaders from Korean soil. Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                        >Dulles</persName> stated that it would be inconsistent for him to join in
                    such a statement, as it would violate the position America had taken in urging
                    United Nations action in the beginning, viz., that the invasion of South Korea
                    was not a domestic civil war but a communist aggression threatening the peace of
                    the world. It was on this very basis that the United Nations had intervened over
                    the opposition of the Soviet bloc’s contention that the war in Korea was a
                    purely domestic issue with which the United Nations had no concern. President
                        <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> and his advisers accepted this
                    viewpoint, and the clause as now appearing in the joint statement was agreed
                        upon.<note n="1" xml:id="d740fn1">For the text of the joint statement as it
                        was issued, see Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, Aug.
                        17, 1953, pp. 203–204.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The Secretary’s draft of the Mutual Defense Treaty<note n="2" xml:id="d740fn2"
                        >For the text of the Draft U.S.-<gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> Mutual
                        Defense Treaty as it was issued, see <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p.
                        204.</note> was presented and despite last ditch arguments and appeals by
                    President <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> for automatic military
                    action was approved with minor changes in text.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Walter S. Robertson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
